{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dc433f83-9f0a-4f15-9eb4-cdab787511cd","content":"Use `dotnet watch test` — it watches for file changes and automatically re-runs your tests:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch test --filter \"RemoveStock_ExceedsAvailable_ThrowsException\"\n```\n\nThe `--filter` flag scopes it to just your failing test so feedback is instant. Every time you save `InventoryServiceTests.cs`, it rebuilds and re-runs.\n\n**Quick tip on your bug:** `RemoveStock` subtracts without validating — it never throws. You'll need to add a guard that throws `InvalidOperationException` when `quantity > available`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"88822edf-4d84-45af-bf94-3302ca6be616","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to set up hot reload for their test project. With .NET and Microsoft.Testing.Platform (as configured in global.json), they can use `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test` to get hot reload for tests.\n\nLet me check which approach works best. Since they're using Microsoft.Testing.Platform runner (configured in global.json), they should be able to use `dotnet test --hotreload` which is a newer feature, or the classic `dotnet watch test`.\n\nLet me suggest `dotnet watch test` which will re-run tests on file changes. Actually, with Microsoft.Testing.Platform and .NET 10, `dotnet test --hotreload` might be available too.\n\n\nI think `dotnet watch test` is the simplest solution here—it monitors for changes and automatically reruns the tests whenever files are modified.","outputTokens":349,"requestId":"0C0C:3E9F58:41D9DE:4CF811:69F00F50"},"id":"ad24b642-5a2e-4066-a507-008d67d82d72","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:37:31.604Z","parentId":"560b390c-af09-4cd6-95a8-dc202e5a2dee"}
